                <p><bibl><ptr target="#gasperini1965"/>, p. <citedRange>83</citedRange> (= <bibl><ptr target="#gasperini2008"/>, p. <citedRange>5</citedRange></bibl>)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#gasperini1967a"/>, p. 166, n. <citedRange>3</citedRange> (= <bibl><ptr target="#gasperini2008"/>, p. <citedRange>77</citedRange></bibl>)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#cdl1970"/>, p. 233, n. <citedRange>2</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>000400</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#mei2013"/>, pp. <citedRange>68-69</citedRange>, pl. <citedRange>XX</citedRange></bibl> (pottery), whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>63.1728</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                   
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63263"><name nymRef="#Ἀρχαῖος">Ἀρχαῖος</name></persName> <orig>α</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Arkhaios A<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p></div>
             <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Archaios A<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Archaios A<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>أرخيوس [---].</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The second word might be either the verb <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἀνέθηκε</foreign> or the name of the deity to whom the vase was dedicated or even
                 (but less plausibly) the father's name of the dedicant.</p>
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#mei2013"/>, pp. <citedRange>68-69</citedRange></bibl> ascribes the vase to the 'painter of Hunting'.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
